history.content:
You need to take 16A, 16B, 70, 126, and 127. Then you are properly prepared for 189 --- which is an advanced undergraduate or beginning graduate level course. 126 and 127 are introductory upper-division courses. One should take introductory upper-divs before advanced upper-divs. 

If you are impatient, 16A, 16B, 70, and 126 can be enough if you have a full mastery of 16B material. Trying to do 189 without the material in 16B is a recipe for failure (or at least great difficulty). Without an understanding of probability at the level of 126 (or at least Stat 140), many of the ideas in 189 will be hard to internalize properly.

Hi,

I am of junior standing and I am trying to take CS 189 soon. I went along with the current eecs curriculum and since there was no requirement for math 54, I have not taken it. Do I need to take it, or is the amount learned in EE16A enough? Is there anything else I should use to prep for the class?

Thanks!
